{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "dbbcc6bf",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<p align=\"center\">\n",
    "  <img src=\"../assets/EcoChem_loc.jpg\" width=\"400\">\n",
    "</p>\n",
    "\n",
    "Here is a presentation of our package, `EcoChem`, a useful tool for anything green chemistry related. Use this package if you want to calculate the PMI and factor E of your reaction, along with plenty of other features!"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "19147bb3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Introduction\n",
    "\n",
    "**Green chemistry** is a very important part of nowadays chemistry, and it is necessary for chemists to take it into account for every reactions they make.\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook has been made to guide you through the use of `EcoChem`, your new favourite tool for green chemistry! Here you will learn how to navigate the interface and how to find the results that interest you. Let's dive in more in details now!"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1fbfc7e6",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Difficulties\n",
    "\n",
    "Before diving in the detailled use of the package, let's mention a few of the points that gave us some trouble along the way.\n",
    "\n",
    "Aside from putting the code together, finding information about solvent density reveals to be quite tricky as some databases rely on approximation and could gave wrong values, limiting the accuracy on our package.<br>\n",
    "Finding the right data proved to be a reccurent chalenge, as it again caused some problems when we were searching through PubChem for pictograms and GHS of the molecules."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "eb7c2de8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## EcoChem use"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a00bf449",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Opening the interface\n",
    "The first step is to open the interface. To do so, run the next cell. You can then refer to this notebook and experiment with the interface in your browser at the same time to see how to use it in details.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "e8aa8acc",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "^C\n"
      "^C\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "!streamlit run ../src/ecochem/interface.py"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "537f8b51",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "It is normal that the cell keeps running, it will until you close it yourself. If you want to exit the app, simply close the tab, and then manually stop this cell."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "589eacc0",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Once the interface is open, you get the opportunity to enter reactants, extractants, product desired and other parameters associated to the reaction.\n",
    "The program will then return you a clean list of anything you could want about your reaction.\n",
    "The beauty of this is that it is very flexible about the accepted format of the molecules. You can use the SMILES of the molecules or even draw them! You don't even need to equilibrate your equation, it will be done for you.\n",
    "\n",
    "You can then easily access information such as **atom economy**, **PMI**, **E-Factor**, **toxicity** of the products, and so much more.\n",
    "\n",
    "It is quite intuitive and easy to use, but we will still guide you through it in the following sections.\n",
    "\n",
    "Additionaly, you can get back to the home page using the `🏠 Home` button in the left sidebar."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0aec27d9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Reaction Builder ⚛️\n",
    "\n",
    "In this section, you get the opportunity to enter all the necessary informations to describe your reaction. Your molecules are stored in dataclasses, and a lot of subfunctions are used to find all the complementray informations needed. These informations are mainly extracted from PubChem using `pubchempy`, and other useful packages such as `thermo`.\n",
    "\n",
    "To enter your reaction in the app, you need to click the `⚛️ Reaction Builder` button in the left sidebar. Now you get to enter your chemicals in either of the following categories:\n",
    "- Reagent\n",
    "- Solvent/Catalyst\n",
    "- Wanted products"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "bcb70673",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Reagents\n",
    "\n",
    "This section is used to input the reactants of your reaction. First press the `➕ Add Reagent` button. You can enter the molecule SMILES in the top bar, or draw it in the cell under it. You'll see the drawing interface is pretty intuitive. Don't forget to press the `Enter` key after writing the SMILES, or click the `Apply` button at the bottom right corner of the drawing interface when you draw a molecule. The reagent's SMILES then appears in a green box under the reagent's interface when it's confirmed.\n",
    "\n",
    "Naturally, you will have several reactants. Use the `➕ Add Reagent` button again to create a new section under the previous one and input your next reactant. If you accidentally created more reagents than you need, use the `❌ Remove` button to delete it."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ace090a1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Solvent/catalyst\n",
    "\n",
    "In this section, you can add eventual solvents or catalysts used for your reaction. It is important to take these into account for the PMI and E-Factor calculations. As previously, you can use the SMILES or drawing option to input your chemicals, and you'll find a `➕ Add Solvent/Catalyst` button if you used several of these. Above the SMILES input, you will find a selector allowing you to chose if you input a solvent or a catalyst. In addition, you are also given the opportunity to input the **density**, **volume** of your solvent or the **mass** of catalyst that you used. You'll find these fields just under the drawing interface."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a5518791",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Wanted products\n",
    "\n",
    "The next section is dedicated to the product that you are synthesizing and the byproducts of your reaction. It is designed as the previous parts, with an `➕ Add Product` button on top and input options for both SMILES and drawing. It is important to note that the first product you input is your **main product**, the one you are interested in. The calculations for PMI, E-factor and atom economy will be made using this product. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c601253e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now that you filled all the informations on this page, you are ready to take the next step! Click the `🚀 Generate Reaction SMILES` button at the bottom of the page to continue.<br>\n",
    "This will generate a visual drawing of your equation of your overall reaction and gives a list of the SMILES of each molecule.<br>\n",
    "If the equation generated does not match what you expected, double-check if the molecules have been entered properly. A mistake probably hides somewhere."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2541c1f7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Compute 🧪\n",
    "\n",
    "Once the `Reaction Builder` part is complete, it is time move on to the next step by clicking `🧪 Compute` in the left sidebar. A new page appears, asking you additional information on your reaction. Those informations are separated in two categories:\n",
    "- Add extractant\n",
    "- Reaction Context & Parameters"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "16c2b834",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Add Extractants (for Work-up)\n",
    "\n",
    "This section is dedicated to any eventual **solvent** you may have used during your reaction to purify your product. They need to be taken into account to determine accurate **PMI** and **E-factor**, so don't forget to indicate them.\n",
    "\n",
    "Here you can find a textbar where you can input an extractant either with its name or its SMILES. Next you need to enter the volume used and its density.\n",
    "Once you input all the informations for one extractant, click the `➕ Add Extractant` button right under the informations and it will appear in a list just under the button.\n",
    "You can then fill the fields again with new informations for another extractant.\n",
    "If you ever add an extractant wrong, you can remove it from the list using the `❌ Remove` button next to its name."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e947f16b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Reaction Parameters\n",
    "\n",
    "This is the final section you need to fill. In here you will fill the desired mass of your main product, and the yield of your reaction. You can either type the values or use the `+` and `-` buttons on the right of the textbar to select the appropriate values.<br>\n",
    "If you ever happen to enter a yield higher than 100 % by accident, don't worry, you did not break the code. You will simply see a message asking you to select a more appropriate yield and you will not be unable to continue until you do so."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ca16464c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Results\n",
    "\n",
    "Once you entered all the data needed in the previous sections, you can click the `⚗️ Compute reaction stoichiometry and Green Metrics` button to access the results."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "259cbd69",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Balanced equation ⚖️\n",
    "\n",
    "The first information that will be given to you is the **balanced reaction**. You don't have to balance it yourself at any point since we do it for you! And if your reaction ever happen to be too long and do not fit on the screen, there is a cursor under the equation that allows you to scroll left and right."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "710bd13c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Green Metrics 🌿\n",
    "\n",
    "This part is by far the more interesting. Here you will find **Atom Economy**, **PMI** and **E-Factor**. Each one of them appears in a box where you can find the value of the parameter in the top-right corner, and a cursor showing you how good or bad is each parameter. Each also comes with a small text comment analysing the parameter.\n",
    "\n",
    "The visualisation is quite easy and takes little time and effort to comprehend, which is quite nice."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e1bd5deb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Risk Assessment ⚠️\n",
    "\n",
    "This part highlights the risks of the reaction, displaying a warning message that depends on the reaction, and the danger pictograms associated to the reaction. These informations are fetched from PubChem."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4761fa01",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Toxicity of Specific Species\n",
    "\n",
    "This last part contains the toxicity associated to each of the species involved in the reaction."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "be5a61e7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Weaknesses\n",
    "\n",
    "Depite the fact that we gave it our all, this package still have some limitations:\n",
    "- If you are interested in several products in your reaction, this package only focuses on one, considering the others as byproducts, as the PMI calculations are made for ONE product. This need to be taken into consideration when entering and analysing the data on the app.\n",
    "- If the compounds used are not present on the database of PubChem the toxicity cannot be returned, same is applicable to the extractant section where the compound can be selected using the IUPAC name.\n",
    "- The interface is laggy for large amout of molecules.\n",
    "- The density of the solvent/extractant must be provided by the user."
   ]
  }
 ],
